    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Modifies the ActionEndpoints.cs file (created by task 040) with feature-flag enforcement; tags include bff-api/api/config/ai; creates an admin disable endpoint with broader-than-normal authorization; touches user-visible enforcement behavior</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>none</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>file-overlap with ActionEndpoints.cs from task 040 — both tasks edit the same file. Task 045 adds (a) feature-flag check on /run and (b) a new admin disable endpoint. Sequential after 040 lands. If task 044 and task 045 both need to edit ActionEndpoints.cs, run them sequentially (conservative).</parallel-reason>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Wire feature-flag + kill-switch enforcement on the Action `/run` endpoint per ADR-018, AND add an admin endpoint to disable a specific Action immediately (kill-switch reference on the Action Definition's `governance` JSON block from FR-01). Feature flags live in typed options classes with startup validation; disabled features return 503 ProblemDetails (ADR-018); flags NEVER bypass authorization (ADR-018 binding). The Action Definition's `governance.killSwitchFlagName` field (Dataverse, from task 010 entity schema) is the per-Action reference; the admin endpoint atomically flips the flag without redeploying the BFF.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    SPAARKE BFF governance + operations engineer fluent in ADR-018 feature flag + kill-switch semantics (options-based, typed, startup-validated, 503 ProblemDetails on disabled), the `IFeatureFlagService` surface (or equivalent — create if not present), and admin-endpoint authorization patterns. You ship kill switches that are reliable, fast, and that NEVER bypass authorization.
  </role>

  <goal>
    Concrete artifacts:
    1. **`Configuration/ActionEngineFeatureFlags.cs`** — typed options class with global flags: `ActionInvocationEnabled` (bool, default true — global kill switch for /run), `ScheduledDispatchEnabled` (bool, default true — global kill switch for the scheduler job handler), `AdminDisableEndpointEnabled` (bool, default true — meta-flag for whether admins can disable Actions at runtime). Startup-validated per ADR-018.
    2. **`Infrastructure/FeatureFlags/IFeatureFlagService.cs`** + **`FeatureFlagService.cs`** — abstraction over BOTH the typed options (compile-time / deploy-time flags) AND the per-Action `governance.killSwitchFlagName` Dataverse field (runtime flags via Action Definition). Method: `Task&lt;bool&gt; IsActionEnabledAsync(Guid actionId, CancellationToken ct)` — returns false if EITHER the global flag is off OR the per-Action governance block has `killSwitchActive = true`. Cache the per-Action flag in `IDistributedCache` (Redis per ADR-009) with a SHORT TTL (30 seconds default) so flips propagate fast across BFF instances.
    3. **`ActionEndpoints.cs` (edit from task 040)** — add a feature-flag endpoint filter `FeatureFlagFilter("ai-action-invocation")` that runs BEFORE the rate limiter and BEFORE the resource authorization filter (so disabled features don't consume rate-limit quota and don't reveal Action existence). Returns 503 ProblemDetails when disabled. On the `/run` endpoint, ALSO check the per-Action kill switch via `IFeatureFlagService.IsActionEnabledAsync(actionId, ct)` after authorization passes (since the per-Action check requires the actionId).
    4. **`Infrastructure/FeatureFlags/FeatureFlagFilter.cs`** — `IEndpointFilter` implementation that checks the global flag and short-circuits with 503 ProblemDetails when disabled. Pluggable by named flag.
    5. **Admin disable endpoint** — `POST /api/ai/actions/{actionId}/admin/disable` and `POST /api/ai/actions/{actionId}/admin/enable`. Authorization: requires `ActionEngine.Admin` role (a new application role — added to the BFF's app registration and to the role check filter). Body: optional reason. Behavior: updates the Action Definition's `governance.killSwitchActive` field in Dataverse, evicts the cache key, emits App Insights event `action_engine.killswitch.toggled` with `actionId`, `state`, `adminOid`, `reason`.
    6. **Tests**:
      - Unit: feature-flag service returns false when global flag is off; false when per-Action kill switch is on; true otherwise.
      - Integration: global flag off → /run returns 503; per-Action kill switch on → /run returns 503 with detail referencing the Action id; admin disable endpoint requires `ActionEngine.Admin` role (regular caller gets 403); after disable, /run returns 503; after enable, /run returns 200.

    Acceptance: ADR-018 binding rules verified — disabled features return 503, flag NEVER bypasses authorization (verified by test that asserts: feature flag is OFF + caller is unauthorized → still 401 from auth, NOT 503 — auth wins over flag).
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      ADR-018 binding rules (MUST):
      - Represent flags in typed options classes with startup validation
      - Return 503 ProblemDetails when feature is disabled
      - Check same flag in both endpoints and async handlers
      - Document default value and environment behavior for each flag

      ADR-018 binding rules (MUST NOT):
      - Use flags to bypass authorization checks (auth runs FIRST; flag check runs AFTER for the unauthorized case to keep behavior consistent)
      - Produce partial behavior when disabled (fail cleanly — 503, not 500)
      - Allow hidden/undocumented kill switches (every flag MUST be documented in `notes/decisions/feature-flags-inventory.md`)

      The Action Engine has TWO layers of flag:
      1. **Global flags** (ActionEngineFeatureFlags typed options class, deploy-time): turn off the entire Action invocation surface or the scheduled dispatch surface. Set via `appsettings.json` or environment variable. Restart required for changes to take effect.
      2. **Per-Action kill switches** (Action Definition's `governance` JSON block from FR-01 / task 010): turn off a specific Action without redeploying. Flipped via the admin endpoint; propagates across BFF instances via Redis cache eviction within ~30 seconds.

      The per-Action kill switch is the operational lever for incident response — "Action X is misbehaving, kill it now without affecting other Actions or redeploying." MVP scope.

      `IFeatureFlagService` does NOT yet exist in the BFF (verified by grep). This task creates it. The service is the abstraction over both layers — callers ask "is this Action enabled" and get a single boolean answer.

      Cache strategy: per-Action flag state cached in `IDistributedCache` (Redis per ADR-009) with 30-second TTL. Cache key: `action-engine:killswitch:{actionId}`. Eviction on admin endpoint mutation. The 30-second TTL is the worst-case propagation delay across instances if a single instance fails to evict (defense in depth). Cache versioning per ADR-009: include the Action's rowversion in the cached value so stale entries are detected.

      Admin role: `ActionEngine.Admin` is a new application role. Added to the BFF app registration's manifest (manifested in `notes/decisions/admin-roles.md` and operator runbook update). For MVP, a global tenant admin or an explicit role assignment is required. The endpoint filter checks `User.IsInRole("ActionEngine.Admin")`.

      Interaction with task 044 (rate limiter): the feature flag check runs BEFORE the rate limiter so disabled features don't consume bucket quota. Pipeline order: auth → feature flag filter → rate limiter → resource authorization filter → handler. The per-Action kill switch is checked INSIDE the handler (or as a late filter) after the actionId is resolved.

      Interaction with task 042 (scheduled job handler): the scheduled dispatch job handler MUST also check `ScheduledDispatchEnabled` (global) AND `IsActionEnabledAsync(actionId)` (per-Action) before invoking the orchestrator. If disabled, return `JobOutcome.Skipped` (NOT `Failed` or `Poisoned` — the message remains processable when the flag is re-enabled, but with idempotency it won't re-run if it succeeded once). NOTE: This requires editing the task 042 handler to add the check. Coordinate or do as part of this task with a clear callout.

      Binding governance: `.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md` MUST be loaded. Placement = BFF. No new NuGet packages (the typed options pattern is in the framework).
    </background>
