  <notes>
    The ADR-018 binding rule "flags never bypass authorization" is the load-bearing constraint. If the flag check runs BEFORE the auth check, an unauthenticated caller can probe whether a feature is enabled (information disclosure). Order MUST be: auth → flag → resource auth → handler. The integration test (c) verifies this.

    Per-Action kill switch is the operational lever. In production, an on-call engineer hits the admin endpoint to disable a runaway Action without redeploying. The 30-second cache TTL is the worst case; typical propagation is sub-second when the cache evicts cleanly.

    The `IFeatureFlagService` abstraction unifies the two flag layers. Callers don't need to know whether a flag is global or per-Action — they ask "is this Action enabled" and get a single answer. This is the right abstraction for operations: incident response writes the kill switch; engineers don't navigate two systems.

    Task 042 (job handler) is edited as part of this task. If task 042 hasn't merged yet, document the dependency and execute task 045 after task 042 lands. If task 042 has merged, this task's edit to the handler is straightforward (insert two lines for the flag check at the start of `HandleAsync`).

    Task 044 (rate limiter) interaction: pipeline order is auth → feature flag filter (this task) → rate limiter (task 044) → resource authorization filter → handler. If both tasks merge in the same PR, double-check the order in `EndpointMappingExtensions.cs` or wherever the pipeline is composed.

    Documentation is binding per ADR-018 ("documented default value and environment behavior for each flag"). `notes/decisions/feature-flags-inventory.md` is NOT optional. Skip it and `adr-check` will catch the gap at Step 9.5.

    Admin role assignment is an operator concern, not a code concern. Document the procedure in `notes/decisions/admin-roles.md` and link from the operator runbook (`docs/guides/auth-deployment-setup.md` update may be appropriate — coordinate if so).
  </notes>

